g.text: UML Diagram: Class IndividualMember in Context
- Move the mouse cursor over a name to see more information.
- Click on a name to go to the corresponding page.
- The arrows of the inheritance tree are

a.title: ― IndividualMember: Distinct element that is not itself a collection (atomic).
a.xlink:title: ― IndividualMember: Distinct element that is not itself a collection (atomic).

a.title: ― ConceptualVariable: A variable at the highest level of abstraction.
a.xlink:title: ― ConceptualVariable: A variable at the highest level of abstraction.

a.title: ― Map: Provides a basic pattern for a comparison map which identifies source and target members and details about their match. Source and target were retained as in describing differences and commonalities the direction of the comparison may be important.
a.xlink:title: ― Map: Provides a basic pattern for a comparison map which identifies source and target members and details about their match. Source and target were retained as in describing differences and commonalities the direction of the comparison may be important.

a.title: ― PhysicalRecordSegment: Description of each physical storage segment required to completely cover a physical record representing the logical record.
a.xlink:title: ― PhysicalRecordSegment: Description of each physical storage segment required to completely cover a physical record representing the logical record.

a.title: ― Member: Element in a collection that can be either atomic (individual member) or composite (collection).
a.xlink:title: ― Member: Element in a collection that can be either atomic (individual member) or composite (collection).

a.title: ― ClassificationIndexEntry: Word or a short phrase corresponding to a classification item in a statistical classification, together with the code of the corresponding classification item.
a.xlink:title: ― ClassificationIndexEntry: Word or a short phrase corresponding to a classification item in a statistical classification, together with the code of the corresponding classification item.

a.title: ― Concept: Unit of thought differentiated by characteristics (from the Generic Statistical Information Model version 1.2: https://statswiki.unece.org/display/clickablegsim/Concept).
a.xlink:title: ― Concept: Unit of thought differentiated by characteristics (from the Generic Statistical Information Model version 1.2: https://statswiki.unece.org/display/clickablegsim/Concept).

a.title: ― ClassificationItem: A space for a category within a statistical classification.
a.xlink:title: ― ClassificationItem: A space for a category within a statistical classification.

a.title: ― DataPoint: Container for an instance value.
a.xlink:title: ― DataPoint: Container for an instance value.

a.title: ― ValueMapping: Physical characteristics for the value of an instance variable stored in a data point as part of a physical segment layout.
a.xlink:title: ― ValueMapping: Physical characteristics for the value of an instance variable stored in a data point as part of a physical segment layout.

a.title: ― Collection: Generic container that supports different types of groupings, from unordered sets to all sorts of hierarchies, nesting and ordered sets/bags.
a.xlink:title: ― Collection: Generic container that supports different types of groupings, from unordered sets to all sorts of hierarchies, nesting and ordered sets/bags.

a.title: ― Agent: Actor that performs a role in relation to a process or product.
a.xlink:title: ― Agent: Actor that performs a role in relation to a process or product.

a.title: ― Code: The characters used as a symbol to designate a category within a codelist or classification. (Formally, a sign for which the signifier is non-linguistic alphanumeric string.)
a.xlink:title: ― Code: The characters used as a symbol to designate a category within a codelist or classification. (Formally, a sign for which the signifier is non-linguistic alphanumeric string.)

a.title: ― Category: Concept whose role is to define and measure a characteristic.
a.xlink:title: ― Category: Concept whose role is to define and measure a characteristic.
